</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2DF0ACA1FFFCFFC3FF71FE2DFEA2FD63" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="description">
<paragraph id="6555FF2AFFFCFFC3FF71FE2DFD98FDB7" blockId="20.[151,1436,474,717]" box="[151,613,510,537]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
(
<figureCitation id="FDD1E3AFFFFCFFC3FF79FE2DFF05FDB7" box="[159,248,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="67.[151,250,1945,1969]" captionTargetBox="[193,1394,196,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@67.[184,1403,181,1922]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURE 14. Southeast Asian Eudocima and Eudocima tyrannus group adults (dorsal aspect)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6605535" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6605535/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs 14</figureCitation>
: G–H, 21: D, 26: P, 32: G, 95:L)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6555FF2AFFFCFFC3FF71FDF1FEA2FD63" blockId="20.[151,1436,474,717]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
The forewing apex is unique with a protracted obliquely rounded lobe (Hampson 1894). The large size is comparable to 
<taxonomicName id="A2EA84A9FFFCFFC3FF3DFD95FEA6FDCE" baseAuthorityName="Guenee" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[219,347,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Eudocima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tyrannus">
<emphasis id="579E2338FFFCFFC3FF3DFD95FEA6FDCE" box="[219,347,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">E. tyrannus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="579E2338FFFCFFC3FE68FD95FDC9FDCF" box="[398,564,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="A2EA84A9FFFCFFC3FE68FD95FDCDFDCF" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[398,560,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Eudocima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sikhimensis">E. sikhimensis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but the hindwing marginal band is greatly reduced and well separated from the wing margin by the orange background color. There is very little black on the underside especially in the marginal areas. The range of this relatively common species includes 
<collectingCountry id="1DFDBFBAFFFCFFC3FCD4FD5DFC93FD07" box="[818,878,655,681]" name="India" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="1DFDBFBAFFFCFFC3FC9FFD5DFC42FD07" box="[889,959,655,681]" name="China" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="1DFDBFBAFFFCFFC3FC2FFD5DFBC4FD07" box="[969,1081,655,681]" name="Indonesia" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
, New 
<collectingCountry id="1DFDBFBAFFFCFFC3FB98FD5DFB32FD07" box="[1150,1231,655,681]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Guinea</collectingCountry>
and the Solomons (
<bibRefCitation id="017B82DBFFFCFFC3FF79FD61FEAEFD63" author="Holloway, J. D." box="[159,339,690,717]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 529" refId="ref38189" refString="Holloway, J. D. (2005) The moths of Borneo (parts 15 and 16): family Noctuidae, subfamily Catocalinae. Malayan Nature Journal, 59 (1 - 4), 1 - 529." type="journal article" year="2005">Holloway 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
